To create a Discord bot with a single slash command (`/ban`) using Discord.js version 14, you'll need to follow these steps. This example assumes you have Node.js installed, and you've created a bot application on the Discord Developer Portal with the bot invite scope and the `Ban Members` permission.

1. **Create a new project directory** and initialize it with `npm init -y` to create a `package.json` file.

2. **Install Discord.js**:
   ```sh
   npm install discord.js@14
   ```

3. **Create your bot file**, for example, `index.js`.

4. **Register your slash command** and handle it. Discord.js v14 introduced a new way to handle slash commands using the `@discordjs/builders` and `@discordjs/rest` packages, which you might need to install additionally if not already included in your discord.js installation.

Here's a basic example of how your `index.js` might look:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, Collection } = require('discord.js');
const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v9');
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require('@discordjs/builders');
const { token, clientId, guildId } = require('./config.json'); // Create a config.json file with your bot's token, client ID, and the guild ID where you want to register the command (or use global commands).

// Create a new client instance
const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, GatewayIntentBits.GuildBans] });

// Login to Discord with your client's token
client.login(token);

// Create a command
const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Bans a user from the server')
  .addUserOption(option =>
    option.setName('target')
      .setDescription('The user to ban')
      .setRequired(true))
  .addStringOption(option =>
    option.setName('reason')
      .setDescription('The reason for the ban')
      .setRequired(false));

// Log when the client is ready
client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Ready! Logged in as ${client.user.tag}`);

  // Register the command
  (async () => {
    const rest = new REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(token);

    try {
      console.log('Refreshing application (/) commands.');

      // Register the command in a specific guild or globally
      const data = await rest.put(
        Routes.applicationGuildCommands(clientId, guildId),
        { body: [banCommand.toJSON()] }
      );

      console.log(`Successfully reloaded (/) commands.`);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
    }
  })();
});

// Handle the interaction creation, which includes slash commands
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isChatInputCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    const target = interaction.options.getUser('target');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    if (target) {
      const member = await interaction.guild.members.fetch(target.id);
      if (member) {
        await member.ban({ reason: reason }).then(() => {
          interaction.reply(`User ${target.tag} has been banned. Reason: ${reason}`);
        }).catch(error => {
          console.error(error);
          interaction.reply('An error occurred while trying to ban the user.');
        });
      } else {
        interaction.reply({ content: 'Cannot find the specified user in this server.', ephemeral: true });
      }
    } else {
      interaction.reply({ content: 'You must specify a user to ban.', ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});
```

Make sure to replace `token`, `clientId`, and `guildId` in `config.json` with your bot's token, client ID, and the guild ID where you want to register the command. If you want to register the command globally, you can use `Routes.applicationCommands(clientId)` instead of `Routes.applicationGuildCommands(clientId, guildId)`.

Remember to run your bot using Node.js, for example, with `node index.js`.

**Important Note**: The `@discordjs/builders`, `@discordjs/rest`, and `discord-api-types` packages are not directly part of the Discord.js library but are officially recommended by the Discord.js team for building and registering slash commands. If you encounter any issues with these packages, ensure you're using compatible versions by checking the Discord.js documentation or package.json file of official Discord.js examples.

Also, ensure your bot has the `Ban Members` permission in the server where you're using this command. If the bot doesn't have the necessary permissions, it won't be able to ban users.

Converting Markdown to HTML can be quite complex due to the numerous features supported by Markdown. However, I'll provide you with a basic C++ function that handles some of the most common Markdown features, such as heading levels 1-6, bold, italic, and paragraphs. This example does not include all Markdown features but should give you a good starting point.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::stringstream htmlStream;
    std::vector<std::string> lines = {""}; // Use a vector to store lines, starting with an empty line for simplicity.
    std::string currentLine;
    std::string currentParagraph;
    bool isInParagraph = false;

    // Split markdown into lines
    for (char c : markdown) {
        if (c == '\n') {
            lines.push_back(currentLine);
            currentLine.clear();
        } else {
            currentLine += c;
        }
    }
    if (!currentLine.empty()) {
        lines.push_back(currentLine);
    }

    // Process each line
    for (const auto& line : lines) {
        if (line.empty()) {
            if (isInParagraph) {
                htmlStream << "</p>" << std::endl;
                isInParagraph = false;
            }
            continue;
        }

        // Check for headings
        if (line[0] == '#') {
            size_t headingLevel = std::min(line.find_first_not_of('#'), line.size() - 1);
            htmlStream << "<h" << headingLevel << ">";
            htmlStream << line.substr(headingLevel + 1) << "</h" << headingLevel << ">" << std::endl;
            continue;
        }

        // Paragraph handling
        if (!isInParagraph) {
            htmlStream << "<p>" << std::endl;
            isInParagraph = true;
        }

        // Bold and italic
        currentParagraph += line;
        std::replace(currentParagraph.begin(), currentParagraph.end(), '*', '_'); // For simplicity, treat * and _ the same
        currentParagraph = std::regex_replace(currentParagraph, std::regex("__(.*?)__"), "<strong>$1</strong>");
        currentParagraph = std::regex_replace(currentParagraph, std::regex("_(.*?)_"), "<em>$1</em>");

        htmlStream << currentParagraph << "<br>" << std::endl; // Use <br> for line breaks within paragraphs
        currentParagraph.clear();
    }

    if (isInParagraph) {
        htmlStream << "</p>" << std::endl;
    }

    return htmlStream.str();
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading 1\n\n*Italic text*\n**Bold text**\n\n## Heading 2\n\nThis is a paragraph.\n\nThis is another paragraph.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function handles basic Markdown features. Note that it uses `<br>` for line breaks within paragraphs, which might not be the standard approach for all Markdown parsers, but it's a simple way to preserve line breaks. The function also simplifies the handling of bold and italic by treating `*` and `_` the same, which might not be perfect but works for basic cases.

For a full-featured Markdown to HTML conversion, you might want to use a library like [cmark](https://github.com/commonmark/cmark) or [md4c](https://github.com/mity/md4c), which support the CommonMark specification and more advanced Markdown features.

